Note: ========================================
Note: ARM Assembly Translator Tests
Note: ========================================
Note: Comprehensive test suite for ARM assembly translation against the
Note: current API: arm_lexer (create_lexer/tokenize/destroy_lexer with the
Note: token list at lexer offset 24, each token's type tag at offset 0),
Note: arm_parser (create_parser/parse/destroy_parser/destroy_arm_node),
Note: arm_to_hir (translate_arm_to_hir / arm_to_hir_from_source producing the
Note: dictionary/list-literal HIR keyed by "type"/"instructions"/"directives"/
Note: "labels"), and hir_to_arm (generate_arm_from_hir).
Note: Coverage: Lexer, Parser, Translation, Generation, Round-trip.
Note: Exit code: number of failed assertions (0 == all passed).
Note: ========================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/arm/arm_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/arm/arm_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/arm/arm_to_hir.runa" as ToHIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/arm/hir_to_arm.runa" as FromHIR
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "tests/test_utils.runa" as TestUtils

Note: Token type tags as defined by arm_lexer.runa.
Constant TOKEN_INSTRUCTION as Integer is 1
Constant TOKEN_REGISTER as Integer is 2
Constant TOKEN_DIRECTIVE as Integer is 3

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Local helpers
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Tokenizes a source string with the real ARM lexer and returns the token list
that hangs at lexer offset 24. The caller reads the list with List.size /
List.get and is responsible for destroying the lexer afterward.
@End Reasoning
Process called "tokenize_source" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer
    Return lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Counts how many tokens in a lexer's token list carry the given type tag
(offset 0). The ARM lexer emits a TOKEN_NEWLINE for line breaks, so counting
by class -- rather than asserting a raw total -- is the robust expression of
"this source produced N instruction / register / directive tokens".
@End Reasoning
Process called "count_tokens_of_type" takes tokens as Integer, type_tag as Integer returns Integer:
    If tokens is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be 0
    Let total be proc size from List with tokens
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than total:
        Let token be proc get from List with tokens, i
        If token is not equal to 0:
            Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
            If token_type is equal to type_tag:
                Set count to count plus 1
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return count
End Process

@Reasoning:
Builds a content-hashed String key and fetches its value from a HIR dictionary
(or operand / statement sub-dictionary). A fresh literal key resolves to the
same entry the frontend stored under, so this is the exact read the backend
performs.
@End Reasoning
Process called "dict_str" takes node as Integer, key as String returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let key_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with key
    Return proc get from Dict with node, key_str
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the entry count of a HIR section list, tolerating a missing (0)
section so counts read uniformly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "list_count" takes lst as Integer returns Integer:
    If lst is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc size from List with lst
End Process

@Reasoning:
Naive O(n*m) substring search used by the round-trip test to confirm the
emitter preserved the mnemonic. The inputs are tiny so the simple scan is
appropriate; both operands are read via StringCore so the match holds across
string representations.
@End Reasoning
Process called "string_contains" takes haystack as Integer, needle as String returns Integer:
    Let haystack_len be proc string_length from StringCore with haystack
    Let needle_len be proc string_length from StringCore with needle
    If needle_len is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    If needle_len is greater than haystack_len:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let i be 0
    Let max_i be haystack_len minus needle_len
    While i is less than or equal to max_i:
        Let matches be 1
        Let j be 0
        While j is less than needle_len:
            Let h_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with haystack, i plus j
            Let n_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with needle, j
            If h_char is not equal to n_char:
                Set matches to 0
                Break
            End If
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Tests
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Smoke test for the ARM lexer: tokenize "mov r0, r1" and assert at least one
token comes out. More specific assertions are in the per-category tests below.
@End Reasoning
Process called "test_lexer_basic" takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc tokenize_source with "mov r0, r1"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "lexer created", lexer
    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let token_count be proc size from List with tokens
    proc assert_greater_than from TestUtils with results, "basic tokenization produces tokens", token_count, 0
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies the lexer recognizes seven common ARM mnemonics as INSTRUCTION-class
tokens. Catches a regression where an alias table update missed a core
instruction (e.g. push/pop dropped after a keyword-set refactor).
@End Reasoning
Process called "test_lexer_instructions" takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc tokenize_source with "mov add sub ldr str push pop"
    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let instr_count be proc count_tokens_of_type with tokens, TOKEN_INSTRUCTION
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "seven instruction tokens", instr_count, 7
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies register tokenization for both numbered (r0, r1) and named
(sp, lr, pc) ARM registers. All five must classify as REGISTER tokens so the
parser can treat them uniformly in operand position.
@End Reasoning
Process called "test_lexer_registers" takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc tokenize_source with "r0 r1 sp lr pc"
    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let reg_count be proc count_tokens_of_type with tokens, TOKEN_REGISTER
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "five register tokens", reg_count, 5
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies numeric literal forms: ARM immediates prefixed with "#", hex
(#0xFF), negative (#-17), and bare decimal (16). The lexer must accept all
four notations and produce a non-empty token stream.
@End Reasoning
Process called "test_lexer_numbers" takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc tokenize_source with "#42 #0xFF #-17 16"
    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let token_count be proc size from List with tokens
    proc assert_greater_than from TestUtils with results, "number tokenization produces tokens", token_count, 0
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies GNU-as directive tokenization: .text, .data, .globl, .section.
Directives must classify as DIRECTIVE tokens to distinguish them from
instructions and labels.
@End Reasoning
Process called "test_lexer_directives" takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc tokenize_source with ".text .data .globl .section"
    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let dir_count be proc count_tokens_of_type with tokens, TOKEN_DIRECTIVE
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "four directive tokens", dir_count, 4
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser Tests
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser builds an AST node for a complete instruction with two
operands (register destination + immediate source). The "has children"
assertion catches a regression where the parser produces a bare instruction
node with no operands attached.
@End Reasoning
Process called "test_parser_instruction" takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc tokenize_source with "mov r0, #42"
    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse from Parser with parser
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "instruction parsed", ast
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 24
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children
    proc assert_greater_than from TestUtils with results, "instruction has operands", child_count, 0
    proc destroy_arm_node from Parser with ast
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser handles a bare label ("main:"). Catches a regression
where the parser requires an instruction or directive after the colon and
rejects label-only lines.
@End Reasoning
Process called "test_parser_label" takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc tokenize_source with "main:"
    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse from Parser with parser
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "label parsed", ast
    proc destroy_arm_node from Parser with ast
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser handles a directive with an argument (.globl main).
Catches a regression where the parser expects directives to be standalone.
@End Reasoning
Process called "test_parser_directive" takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc tokenize_source with ".globl main"
    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse from Parser with parser
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "directive parsed", ast
    proc destroy_arm_node from Parser with ast
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser handles ARM memory-operand syntax with base register plus
immediate offset ([r1, #4]). This stresses the bracket-balancing logic and
the inner comma-separated operand list.
@End Reasoning
Process called "test_parser_memory" takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc tokenize_source with "ldr r0, [r1, #4]"
    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse from Parser with parser
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "memory operand parsed", ast
    proc destroy_arm_node from Parser with ast
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser handles register-list syntax used by push/pop
({r0, r1, lr}). The curly-brace list with commas is parsed as a single
operand and the parser must accumulate registers until the closing brace.
@End Reasoning
Process called "test_parser_register_list" takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc tokenize_source with "push {r0, r1, lr}"
    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse from Parser with parser
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "register list parsed", ast
    proc destroy_arm_node from Parser with ast
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Translation Tests
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
End-to-end check from ARM source to HIR with structural verification via
arm_to_hir_from_source. The HIR contract is a dictionary with "type" =
"arm_assembly" and an "instructions" key; this catches a regression where the
translator returns non-null but malformed HIR.
@End Reasoning
Process called "test_arm_to_hir" takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc arm_to_hir_from_source from ToHIR with "mov r0, #42"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "HIR created from ARM source", hir
    Let type_value be proc dict_str with hir, "type"
    Let type_ok be proc string_equals from StringCore with type_value, "arm_assembly"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "HIR type is arm_assembly", type_ok, 1
    Let instrs be proc dict_str with hir, "instructions"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "HIR has instructions field", instrs
    Let instr_count be proc list_count with instrs
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "one instruction lowered", instr_count, 1
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reverse direction: lower a single instruction to HIR, then emit it back via
generate_arm_from_hir and assert it produces non-empty output. Exercises the
emitter against a real (not hand-rolled) HIR dictionary.
@End Reasoning
Process called "test_hir_to_arm" takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc arm_to_hir_from_source from ToHIR with "mov r0, #42"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "HIR for generation created", hir
    Let arm_output be proc generate_arm_from_hir from FromHIR with hir
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "ARM generated from HIR", arm_output
    Let out_len be proc string_length from StringCore with arm_output
    proc assert_greater_than from TestUtils with results, "generated ARM is non-empty", out_len, 0
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Round-Trip Test
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Full pipeline: ARM source -> HIR -> ARM text. The "contains 'mov'" assertion
confirms the emitter wrote the instruction mnemonic rather than producing an
empty or garbled string.
@End Reasoning
Process called "test_round_trip" takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc arm_to_hir_from_source from ToHIR with "mov r0, #42"
    Let generated be proc generate_arm_from_hir from FromHIR with hir
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "round-trip completed", generated
    Let contains_mov be proc string_contains with generated, "mov"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip contains 'mov'", contains_mov, 1
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Suite entry point
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Let results be proc create_test_results from TestUtils
    proc begin_suite from TestUtils with results, "ARM assembly translator suite"

    proc test_lexer_basic with results
    proc test_lexer_instructions with results
    proc test_lexer_registers with results
    proc test_lexer_numbers with results
    proc test_lexer_directives with results

    proc test_parser_instruction with results
    proc test_parser_label with results
    proc test_parser_directive with results
    proc test_parser_memory with results
    proc test_parser_register_list with results

    proc test_arm_to_hir with results
    proc test_hir_to_arm with results
    proc test_round_trip with results

    proc print_summary from TestUtils with results
    Let failed be proc get_failed from TestUtils with results
    proc destroy_test_results from TestUtils with results

    Return failed
End Process
